<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
<worksheet xml:id="worksheet-hormone-halflife">
  <title>Hormone Half-Lives and Exponential Decay</title>

  <p>
    In this worksheet, we use differential equations to model how medication
    levels change over time. Our goal is <em>not</em> to make medical recommendations
    or predict any individual person’s experience. Instead, we build simplified
    mathematical models that help us understand how medication levels evolve
    after treatment changes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gender-affirming hormone therapy provides one example where these questions
    arise in a social and policy context. Clinical guidelines recommend monitoring
    hormone levels during treatment because concentrations change gradually over
    time rather than instantly.
  </p>

  <exercise xml:id="halflife-model">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a medication has concentration <m>H(t)</m> in the bloodstream at
        time <m>t</m>. A simple model assumes the body removes the medication at a
        rate proportional to the amount currently present:
      </p>

      <me>\frac{dH}{dt} = -kH.</me>

      <p>
        Here:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><m>H(t)</m> is the hormone concentration at time <m>t</m>,</li>
        <li><m>k &gt; 0</m> is the elimination rate constant,</li>
        <li><m>t</m> is measured in days.</li>
      </ul>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="halflife-solution">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Solve the differential equation
      </p>

      <me>\frac{dH}{dt} = -kH</me>

      <p>
        with initial condition <m>H(0) = H_0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="halflife-constant">
    <statement>
      <p>
        The <em>half-life</em> of a medication is the time required for its
        concentration to decrease to half its initial value.
      </p>

      <p>
        If the half-life is <m>T_{1/2}</m>, show that the constant <m>k</m> satisfies
      </p>

      <me>k = \frac{\ln 2}{T_{1/2}}.</me>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="testosterone-example">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A commonly prescribed injectable testosterone formulation has an
        approximate half-life of <m>8</m> days.
      </p>

      <p>
        Using <m>T_{1/2} = 8</m>, compute the value of <m>k</m>. Then write the
        concentration function in the form
      </p>

      <me>H(t) = H_0 e^{-kt}.</me>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="percent-remaining">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a patient has concentration <m>H_0</m> at the moment treatment is
        stopped.
      </p>

      <p>
        How much remains after:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li><m>8</m> days?</li>
        <li><m>16</m> days?</li>
        <li><m>24</m> days?</li>
        <li><m>32</m> days?</li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        Express each answer as a percentage of <m>H_0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="policy-reflection">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A policy that abruptly interrupts access to medication may be described
        informally as “just stopping treatment.”
      </p>

      <p>
        Based on the model above, explain why this phrase is mathematically
        incomplete. Consider the role of half-life, dosage schedule, and the
        difference between stopping a prescription and the body immediately
        returning to a previous physiological state.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

</worksheet>
